Decision Tree Classifier (Income Prediction)

Instructor: Vijay Gurbani (Chief Data Scientist at Vail Systems, Inc)

Project Summary

  • Analyzed a dataset to predict whether individuals earn more or less than $50K based on demographic and financial features.
  • Cleaned and prepared the dataset, handling missing values and feature selection.
  • Constructed a decision tree classifier to predict income levels and evaluated model performance with accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity metrics.
  • Compared the performance of balanced and imbalanced datasets to identify the most effective approach.

Libraries Used: rpart, rpart.plot, caret

Key Findings

The decision tree classifier revealed significant predictors such as education, relationship status, and capital gain. The first model achieved a balanced accuracy of 81%, while the second model (with a balanced dataset) showed a sensitivity of 94% but a lower balanced accuracy of 73%. This highlights the trade-off between balancing datasets and overall performance.

Data Visualizations

Decision trees and confusion matrices were used to visually assess the model’s performance. A decision tree plot clearly demonstrated how different features influenced the income prediction. Additionally, scatter plots provided insight into feature distributions.

Conclusions

This project demonstrates my ability to build, evaluate, and optimize machine learning models using decision trees. It underscores the importance of data preprocessing and balancing techniques to improve model accuracy. The insights gained from comparing different models showcase the complexities of trade-offs in predictive modeling.

Data Cleaning and Preparation

I started by loading and cleaning the 'adult-test.csv' and 'adult-train.csv' datasets. This involved removing rows with missing values across various attributes such as age, education, and income. Ensuring the data is clean is a crucial step in building reliable models, as it helps prevent issues that could arise from incomplete data. After cleaning, I verified the dimensions of both datasets to confirm the number of observations and features. 


setwd("C:/Users/directory-removed")

Model 1 Analysis and Development

Next, I built a decision tree classifier using the 'rpart' library in R. The model was trained on the cleaned training dataset, with income as the target variable. 

set.seed(1122)
model <- rpart(income ~ . , data = train, method = "class")

rpart.plot(model, extra=104, fallen.leaves=T, type=4, main="1994 US Census Database Decision Tree")



Key Predictors and Initial Split

Q: What are the top three predictors in your decision tree model for income classification?
A: The top three predictors identified by the decision tree model are education, relationship status, and capital gain.

Q: What was the first attribute split in the decision tree, and what was the predicted class?
A: The first split in the decision tree was made based on the relationship attribute. The predicted class for the first node was individuals earning <=50K.

Q: What was the distribution of observations in the first node after the initial split?
A: The distribution of observations at the first node was 75% for individuals earning <=50K and 25% for individuals earning >50K.




Summary

In my decision tree model, the top three predictors influencing income classification were education, relationship status, and capital gain. The first split in the decision tree occurred on the relationship attribute, with the predicted class for the first node being individuals earning <=50K. At this point, the distribution of observations was 75% for the <=50K class and 25% for the >50K class, showing that relationship status plays a significant role in the model’s initial prediction.







Model Evaluation: Confusion Matrix and Metrics

To evaluate the model, I used a confusion matrix to calculate important performance metrics, including accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity. The accuracy of the model was 83.9%, with a high sensitivity of 94.82% and a specificity of 50.35%. These metrics give insight into how well the model can correctly classify individuals who earn less than $50K (high sensitivity) but show the challenge of correctly identifying individuals earning more than $50K (lower specificity). 

pred <- predict(model, test, type="class")
print(confusionMatrix(as.factor(pred), as.factor(test[, 15])))

TP <- 10772
TN <- 1863
FN <- 1837
FP <- 588

sensitivity <- TP / (TP + FN)
specificity <- TN / (TN + FP)
balanced_accuracy <- (sensitivity + specificity) / 2
balanced_error_rate <- 1 - balanced_accuracy

cat(paste(" Sensitivity:", round(sensitivity, 2), "\n"),
    paste("Specificity:", round(specificity, 2), "\n"),
    paste("Balanced Accuracy:", round(balanced_accuracy, 2), "\n"),
    paste("Balanced Error Rate:", round(balanced_error_rate, 2)))
 Sensitivity: 0.85 
 Specificity: 0.76 
 Balanced Accuracy: 0.81 
 Balanced Error Rate: 0.19

Model Performance Metrics

Sensitivity: 85%
This means that the model correctly identifies 85% of individuals who earn <=$50K. In other words, it is very effective at detecting people in this income group.

Specificity: 76%
The model correctly identifies 76% of individuals who earn more than $50K. While not as high as sensitivity, it still performs well at recognizing individuals in the higher income bracket.

Balanced Accuracy: 81%
Balanced accuracy combines sensitivity and specificity to give an overall measure of how well the model performs across both income groups. At 81%, the model shows strong, well-rounded performance.

Balanced Error Rate: 19%
This indicates that the model makes errors in about 19% of cases across both income groups. A lower error rate demonstrates better reliability.







ROC Curve and Area Under the Curve (AUC)

I further evaluated the model by plotting the ROC curve and calculating the area under the curve (AUC), which came out to 0.84. The AUC is a valuable metric because it measures the ability of the classifier to distinguish between classes. A higher AUC indicates a better-performing model, with 0.84 representing a strong classifier for this dataset. 

library(ROCR)
predicted_ROC <- prediction(predict(model, type = "prob")[, 2], train$income)

# plot ROC curve
roc_curve <- performance(predicted_ROC, "tpr", "fpr")
plot(roc_curve, col="blue", main="ROC Curve", lwd = 2)

# diagonal line
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lwd = 2, col = "red", lty = 2)

# perfect classifier line
lines(c(0, 0, 1), c(0, 1, 1), lwd = 2, col = "purple")

legend("bottomright", legend = c("Random Classifier", "Perfect Classifier", "Current Classifier"),
       lty = c(1, 1, 1), lwd = 2, col = c("red", "purple", "blue"))


area_under_the_curve <- performance(predicted_ROC, measure = "auc")
area_under_the_curve <- area_under_the_curve@y.values[[1]]
abline(0, 1, lty = 2)


cat("Area Under the Curve: ", area_under_the_curve, "\n")
Area Under the Curve:  0.8430714



Cross-Validation and Tree Pruning

I used cross-validation to determine the optimal size of the decision tree. The complexity parameter (CP) table showed that the tree at size 4 had the lowest cross-validation error, indicating that pruning the tree beyond this point would not improve performance. By stopping at the optimal size, I ensured that the model avoided overfitting, while still maintaining good accuracy. 

printcp(model)

Class Imbalance and Balancing the Dataset

To address the imbalance between classes in the dataset (with significantly more people earning <=$50K than >$50K), I under-sampled the majority class. After balancing the dataset, I retrained the decision tree classifier. The new balanced model helped mitigate the class imbalance, but it also resulted in different performance metrics. Specifically, the sensitivity increased to 94%, but the specificity decreased to 52%. This trade-off reflects the challenge of improving performance across both classes. 

set.seed(1122)

less_or_equal_to_50 <- nrow(train[train$income == '<=50K', ])
greater_than_50 <- nrow(train[train$income == '>50K', ])
cat(" Less or equal to 50K: ", less_or_equal_to_50,"\n",
    "Greater than 50K: ", greater_than_50, "\n")
 Less or equal to 50K:  22653 
 Greater than 50K:  7508 



train_less_or_equal_to_50 <- train[train$income == '<=50K', ]
under_sample_train_less_or_equal_to_50 <- train_less_or_equal_to_50[sample(nrow(train_less_or_equal_to_50), greater_than_50, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL), ]

train_greater_than_50 <- train[train$income == '>50K', ]
cat(" Less or equal to 50K: ",nrow(under_sample_train_less_or_equal_to_50),"\n",
    "Greater than 50K: ", nrow(train_greater_than_50), "\n")
 Less or equal to 50K:  7508 
 Greater than 50K:  7508 
balanced_train <- rbind(under_sample_train_less_or_equal_to_50,train_greater_than_50)

pred <- predict(model_2, test, type="class")

Key Findings

In comparing the two models, the first model had a sensitivity of 85%, specificity of 76%, and a balanced accuracy of 81%. The second model, which used a balanced dataset, achieved a higher sensitivity of 94%, but its specificity dropped to 52%, and the balanced accuracy was 73%. Both models had a similar Area Under the Curve (AUC).

Conclusion

While the second model improved sensitivity by balancing the dataset, it did not enhance overall performance, as evidenced by the lower specificity and balanced accuracy. The first model performed better in terms of balanced accuracy and specificity. The discrepancy in performance can be attributed to the unbalanced nature of the test dataset, which affected the second model's ability to generalize well across income groups.
